INSERT INTO `ai_chat_history` (`id`, `user_id`, `question`, `answer`, `created_at`) VALUES
(7, 3, 'what is life cycle', 'Life Cycle\n\nA life cycle is the series of stages that something goes through from its beginning to its end. It shows how an organism, product, project, or idea starts, grows, changes, and eventually finishes or repeats the process. Think of it like a story with a clear start, middle, and finish, where each part has its own characteristics and tasks.\n\nKey Points:\n- Begins with a starting point such as a seed, idea, or launch.\n- Moves through growth or development phases where changes happen.\n- Reaches a mature or peak stage where it performs its main function.\n- Ends with decline, completion, or renewal, sometimes starting a new cycle.\n\nExample:\nA butterfly’s life cycle starts when a female butterfly lays eggs (start). The eggs hatch into caterpillars that eat and grow (growth). The caterpillar then forms a chrysalis and changes into a butterfly (maturity). The adult butterfly lives, mates, and lays new eggs, beginning the cycle again (renewal).', '2026-06-10 02:48:07'),
(8, 3, 'what is newton law', 'Newton\'s Laws of Motion\n\nNewton\'s laws describe how objects move and interact with forces. The first law says an object will stay still or keep moving straight at constant speed unless a force pushes or pulls it. The second law explains that when a force acts on an object, it changes the object\'s motion; the bigger the force, the faster the change, and heavier objects need more force to change their speed. The third law tells us that forces always come in pairs: if one object pushes another, the second object pushes back with the same strength in the opposite direction.\n\nKey Points:\n- First law (inertia): objects keep their current state of motion unless acted on by an external force.\n- Second law: Force = mass  acceleration; more force means more acceleration, more mass means less acceleration for the same force.\n- Third law: For every action force, there is an equal and opposite reaction force.\n\nExample:\nWhen you ride a bicycle and pedal harder, you apply a larger force on the pedals. This force makes the bike accelerate faster because the bike’s mass stays the same. If you try to push a heavy shopping cart, you need to apply a stronger push than you would for a light cart, showing the relationship between force, mass, and acceleration. When the bike’s tire pushes backward against the road, the road pushes the tire forward with an equal and opposite force, propelling the bike forward.', '2026-06-10 02:49:19'),
(9, 3, 'who is george warshington', 'George Washington\n\nGeorge Washington was the first President of the United States and one of the leading figures in America’s fight for independence from Britain. He helped lead the colonial army during the Revolutionary War, and after the war he helped create the new government. People call him “the Father of His Country” because of his important role in starting the nation.\n\nKey Points:\n- Commanded the Continental Army and won the Revolutionary War.\n- Served two terms as the first President of the United States (1789‑1797).\n- Set many precedents for how the presidency works, such as serving only two terms.\n- Was a farmer and owned a plantation called Mount Vernon in Virginia.\n- Known for his honesty, leadership, and dedication to the new country.\n\nExample:\nImagine a school class that needs a leader to organize a group project. George Washington was like the class captain who guided his teammates (the colonies) through a big challenge (the war) and then helped set the rules for future class projects (the new government). His example shows how good leadership and fair decisions can shape the future.', '2026-06-10 02:52:29'),
(25, 3, 'what is momentun', 'Momentum\n\nMomentum is a measure of how much motion an object has. It depends on two things: how heavy the object is (its mass) and how fast it is moving (its velocity). The more mass an object has or the faster it moves, the more momentum it carries. Momentum helps explain why it is harder to stop a moving truck than a rolling marble, even if both are moving at the same speed.\n\nKey Points:\n- Momentum (p) = mass (m) × velocity (v)\n- It is a vector, meaning it has both size and direction.\n- In a closed system (no outside forces), total momentum stays the same – this is called conservation of momentum.\n- A larger mass or higher speed results in larger momentum.\n\nExample:\nThink of riding a bike downhill. When you start moving slowly, you can stop quickly by pressing the brakes. As you pick up speed, you feel it gets harder to stop because your bike’s momentum has increased. If you add a heavy backpack, even at the same speed, you’ll need to apply more force or take a longer distance to come to a stop, showing how both mass and velocity affect momentum.', '2026-06-12 08:59:52');

